				\begin{document}$$\sigma =\frac{L}{R\cdot A}$$\end{document}S-CNF paper with a thickness of 28 µm was used to fabricate a membrane electrode assembly (MEA). The catalyst ink was a mixture of Pt/C (Tanaka Kikinzoku Kogyo K.K., Japan, 46.2 wt% Pt) and 5 wt% Nafion (Sigma Aldrich, Japan), ethanol (Sigma Aldrich, Japan), and deionized water. Whilst nanocellulose will be explored in the future as an electrode ionomer in its own right, at this stage it is important to investigate these new membranes using state-of-the-art electrocatalyst layers. The catalyst ink was stirred overnight, and sonicated for 30 min before use (SMT Ultra Sonic Homogenizer UH-600). Catalyst ink was sprayed onto the membranes (Nordson K.K. Spraying Device, C-3J) with an electrode size of 0.5 cm2, and a loading of 0.3 mgPt cm− 2 at both the anodeand cathode. The MEA was then sandwiched between hydrophobic carbon paper gas diffusion layers (GDLs, EC-TP1-060T) at 0.2 kN for 190 s at 132 °C.
